ia, who are struggling to make a home for themselves in Amsterdam and Rome. By explaining how real people navigate through the difficulties of their displacement as well as the numerous scenarios and barriers to their emplacement, the author sheds new light on our understanding of what it is like to be a refugee.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aForced migrationzYugoslavia. 0aYugoslavsxCultural assimilationzItalyzRome. 0aYugoslavsxCultural assimilationzNetherlandszAmsterdam. 0aYugoslavsxMigrations. 0aYugoslavszItalyzRomexEthnic identity. 0aYugoslavszItalyzRomexSocial conditions. 0aYugoslavszNetherlandszAmsterdamxEthnic identity. 0aYugoslavszNetherlandszAmsterdamxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311099828340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184545956740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781845459567423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781845459567/original  a978-3-11-099828-3  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK